ownedComment.body: Author:No Magic, Inc.. Created:. Title:Introduction to SysML. Comment:.
For more information, see Section 5.5.4 Numbering Requirement IDs in SysML Plugin UserGuide.pdf.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> A Requirement specifies a capability or condition that must (or should) be satisfied. A Requirement may specify a function that a system must perform or a performance condition a system must achieve. SysML provides modeling constructs to represent text-based Requirements and relate them to other modeling elements. </body>
</html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> The unique id of the Requirement. </body>
</html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> The textual representation or a reference to the textual representation of the Requirement. </body>
</html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> A Constraint Block is a Block that packages the statement of a Constraint so it may be applied in a reusable way to constrain Properties of other Blocks. A Constraint Block typically defines one or more Constraint Parameters, which are bound to Properties of other Blocks in a surrounding context where the Constraint is used. Binding Connectors are used to bind each parameter of the Constraint Block to a Property in the surrounding context. All Properties of a Constraint Block are Constraint Parameters, with the exception of Constraint Properties that hold internally nested usages of other Constraint Blocks. </body>
</html>

A Constraint Block may not own any structural or behavioral elements beyond the Properties that define its Constraint Parameters, Constraint Properties that hold internal usages of Constraint Blocks, Binding Connectors between its internally nested Constraint Parameters, constraint expressions that define an interpretation for the Constraint Block, and general-purpose model management and cross-cutting elements.
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Double-click this Block to open its SysML Parametric Diagram. </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Any classifiers which specializes a Constraint Block must also have the <font face="Arial, sans-serif">«</font>ConstraintBlock<font face="Arial, sans-serif">»</font> stereotype applied. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Any Properties of a Block that is typed by a Constraint Block must have composite aggregation. </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> Binding Connectors are used to bind each Constraint Parameter of the Constraint Block to a Property in the surrounding context. </body>
</html>
The behavior allocation of Actions to Parts are created by using the AllocateActivityPartition. See the activity diagram "Pump" for more information.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> The <font face="Arial, sans-serif">«a</font><font face="Arial">llocated</font><font face="Arial, sans-serif">»</font> stereotype is automatically applied to both source and target elements of an Allocate relationship. </body>
</html>
Double-click to open the specification dialog, and select the Traceability property group, in order to see the new derived properties for Traceability

Right-click the Suppress Context-Specific Values part to use the shortcut menu to show/hide the context-specific value compartment of the selected part symbol.

 

The Suppress Context-Specific Values symbol property of a part symbol can also be used for the similar purpose.
These context-specific value compartments show the different dimensions of cylinders which are used by the Car and SuperCar Blocks.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> The SysML Value Propagation capability can be turned on / off in the Project Options dialog: Propagate SysML Values. For more information on SysML Value Propagation, see the SysML Plugin User Guide in the 'manual' folder of MagicDraw's installation directory. </body> </html>
Note: Port conjugation can be used when a pair of Ports with the same type is connected to.
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> An ItemFlow itemProperty is typed by a ValueType, Block, or Signal. </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> If an ItemFlow has an itemProperty, one of the classifiers of conveyed items must be the same as the type of the item property. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Item property cannot have a value if the item flow is realized by an Association. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> If an ItemFlow has an itemProperty, its name should be the same as the name of the item flow. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> ItemProperty is a property of the common (possibly indirect) owner of the source and the target. </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> A Connector or an Association, or an inherited Association must exist between the source and the target of the InformationFlow </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> <font size="2">Usage -> Required Interface</font> </body>
</html>
Interface Realization -> Provided Interface
A valid Connector could be created between a standard Port (on the left) and a Conjugated Port (on the right), having the same type.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> A Flow Property is typed by a ValueType, Block, or Signal. </body>
</html>

Note: A Non-atomic Flow Port could be connected to another Conjugated Flow Port of the same type. Therefore, there is no need to create another Flow Specification having similar Flow Properties with the opposing directions. To achieve that, simply type another Flow Port with the same Flow Specification and set the isConjugated attribute of such Flow Port to True.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Full ports cannot be proxy ports either. This applies even if some of the stereotypes are on subset or redefined ports. </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Binding connectors cannot link full ports to other composite properties of the block owning the port, except ports that are not full. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Full ports cannot be behavioral (isBehavior=false). </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Full ports cannot be conjugated (isConjugated=false). </body> </html>

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> The arrow notation on the port symbol indicates a consequence direction of flow properties owned by type of port. </body> </html>
Proxy ports cannot be full ports either. This applies even if some of the stereotypes are on subset or redefined ports.
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Proxy ports can only be typed by interface blocks. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Ports owned by the type of a proxy port must be proxy ports. </body> </html>
Figure 9.7 Usage example of proxy and full ports

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Interface blocks cannot own or inherit behaviors, or have classifier behaviors or methods for their behavioral features. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Interface blocks cannot have composite properties that are not ports. </body> </html>
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Ports owned by interface blocks can only be typed by interface blocks. </body> </html>
DirectedFeature can only be applied to behavioral features or to properties that do not have FlowProperty applied, including on subset or redefined features
<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> Operations that are not provided must not have or inherit methods. </body> </html>
If the value of isEncapsulated of a Block is false or not present, Connectors can be connected to the Block's internal structure.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head> <body> A Block is a modular unit that describes the structure of a system or element. It may include both structural and behavioral features, such as Properties and Operations, that represent the state of the system and behavior that the system may exhibit. Some of these Properties may hold parts of a system, which can also be described by Blocks. A Block may include a structure of Connectors between its Properties to indicate how its Parts or other Properties are related to one another. </body> </html>

To apply the «AllocateActivityPartition» stereotype to the Swimlane, right-click the Swimlane header, and then select Allocated Activity Partition to mark it with the check symbol in the shortcut menu.

sysml:Requirement.Text: Maximum speed should be greater than or equal to 200 km/h
The total cubic capacity of the engine should be less than 1,600cc
The total house power should be greater than or equal to 100 hp at 6000-6500 rpm.
The fuel consumption should be better than 20 km/lite (without traffic)
The car should be able to accelerate from 0 to 100 km/h within 8.5 s. and from 100 to the maximum speed within 20 s.
Maximum torque should be greater than or equal to 140 N-m at 4,000-5,000 rpm
